se as French <i>Tirand</i> ‘one who pulls on the reins’, hence ‘obstinate, stubborn’. This name may have become confused with   Turrell  . A branch of this Anglo-Norman family has been in Ireland since the 12th century. Its name has been Gaelicized as <b>Tirial</b>.","English: habitational name from Tirril (Cumbria), which derives from Old Norse <i>tyri</i> ‘resinous wood’ + <i>erg</i> ‘shieling’."]},{"name":"Therrell","meanings":["Apparently an altered form or a variant of English   Terrell  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Heron","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably a derivative of Welsh <i>aer</i> ‘battle’; borne in Celtic mythology by the goddess of battle, known in a Latinized form as <i>Agrona</i>. Modern use may have been influenced by the word <i>aeron</i> ‘fruit, berries’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Heron Terrell was born in 1370, in Essex, England as the son of Walter Tyrrell an